        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Alfred House | Gipsy Hill | Upper Norwood | S.E.</placeName>
                    <date>1 Oct 1880.</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir,</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I am very much obliged to you for your kind letter of 29 which reached me last night.<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
<p>I shall be most happy to dine with you in accordance with your kind invitation if you will kindly allow me to come in ordinary dress, my evening clothes having been already sent on with my heavy baggage to Brindisi.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>It is very good of you to offer to put me up for the night, but as I am living so near to Beckenham I can easily return here after dinner.<ref target="#foot.f3"/> I came home on a very short holiday indeed &amp; have been in London only since Sunday last. I must leave again in about a week &amp; I regret to say I have only two evenings left free, namely Sunday &amp; Monday next, on either of which I should, as may be convenient for you, be most happy to dine with you.<ref target="#foot.f4"/></p>
<p>I am glad that my notes on worm casts have proved of some use<ref target="#foot.f5"/></p>
<p>Believe me to be | Yrs sincerely | George King <lb resp="#mjhawkins"/></p>
<p rend="left">C. Darwin Esq</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-12730.xml">letter to George King, 29 September 1880</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">From 1871, the Italian port of Brindisi became the terminus for P&amp;O ships sailing to India. Passengers and cargoes travelled to Brindisi by train, from where ships left for India every Sunday at 2<hi rend="smallCaps">pm</hi> (‘The Old Peninsula &amp; Oriental Steam Navigation Company <hi rend="italic">c</hi> 1835–1972’, http://www.pandosnco.co.uk/indianmail.html (accessed 16 May 2019); see also <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_11115.xml">Howarth and Howarth 1994</ref>, p. 69). <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2693.xml">King</ref> was superintendent of the Royal Botanic Garden in Calcutta.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">Upper Norwood was just over three miles from Beckenham.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">King probably dined with CD on Monday 4 October; see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-12735.xml">letter to George King, 2 October 1880</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-12730.xml">letter to George King, 29 September 1880</ref> and n. 4.</note>
        </div>
    
